{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti chapter 8, a person of lower varṇa (a \"low-born man,\" i.e., non-twice-born or Śūdra) who strikes or injures a superior (a Brahmin) with a limb faces amputation of that same limb.**[^1]\n\nThis is specified in verses 8.279–280: \"With whatever limb a low-born man should injure a superior, that very limb of his shall be cut off; this is the ordinance of Manu. He who raises his hand or a stick deserves to have his hand cut off; he who strikes in anger with his foot deserves to have his foot cut off.\"[^2] The text treats such inter-varṇa violence severely to maintain hierarchy, contrasting with fines for lesser injuries (e.g., breaking skin: 100 paṇas) or equals.[^3]\n\nFor context, verbal insults by a Kṣatriya against a Brahmin incur a fine of 100 paṇas, but physical assault escalates dramatically for inferiors.[^4] Non-Brahmin here implies Śūdra (or outcaste), as Kṣatriya/Vaiśya assaults on Brahmins follow graded fines rather than amputation in this section.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, ch. 8, [full chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, ch. 8, verses 279–280, [paragraphs p-526528 to p-c0dabc](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-526528).\n\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, ch. 8, verse 284, [paragraph p-ef92cd](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-ef92cd).\n\n[^4]: Manusmṛti, ch. 8, verse 267, [paragraph p-2ca524](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-2ca524).\n\n[^5]: Manusmṛti, ch. 8, verses 276–277, [paragraphs p-84e4c4 to p-51705f](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-84e4c4).",
